Bank Marketing Campaign

Overview

Data Set Information:

The data is related with direct marketing campaigns of a banking institution. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. Often, more than one contact to the same client was required, in order to assess if the product (bank term deposit) would be (yes) or not (no) subscribed.

Attribute Descriptions

Bank Client Data

1 - age: (numeric)
2 - job: Type of job (Categorical: admin.,blue-collar,entrepreneur,housemaid,management,retired,self-employed,services,student,technician,unemployed,unknown)
3 - marital: Marital status (Categorical: divorced,married,single,unknown; note: divorced means divorced or widowed)
4 - education: (Categorical: primary, secondary, tertiary and unknown)
5 - default: Has credit in default? (Categorical: no,yes,unknown)
6 - housing: Has housing loan? (Categorical: no,yes,unknown)
7 - loan: Has personal loan? (Categorical: no,yes,unknown)
8 - balance: Account balance of the individual.

Information regarding most recent contact of current campaign

9 - contact: Contact communication type (Categorical: cellular,telephone)
10 - month: Last contact month of year (Categorical: jan, feb, mar, , nov, dec)
11 - day: Last contact day of the week (Categorical: mon,tue,wed,thu,fri)
12 - duration: Last contact duration, in seconds (Numeric)
13 - campaign: Number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (Numeric, includes last contact)

Previous Campaign Information

14 - pdays: Number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (Numeric; -1 means client was not previously contacted)
15 - previous: Number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client (Numeric)
16 - poutcome: Outcome of the previous marketing campaign (Categorical: failure,nonexistent,success)

Response Variable

17 - y: Whether a client has subscribed to a term deposit (Binary: yes,no)

Formatting

# Rename month values
df$month <- recode(df$month, jan = "January",
                             feb = "February",
                             mar = "March",
                             apr = "April",
                             may = "May",
                             jun = "June",
                             jul = "July",
                             aug = "August",
                             sep = "September",
                             oct = "October",
                             nov = "November",
                             dec = "December")

# Formatting: Capitalize values for presentation
df <- df %>% mutate(month = as.factor(month),
                    job = as.factor(capitalize(job)),
                    default = as.factor(capitalize(default)),
                    education = as.factor(capitalize(education)),
                    marital = as.factor(capitalize(marital)),
                    housing = as.factor(capitalize(housing)),
                    contact = as.factor(capitalize(contact)),
                    loan = as.factor(capitalize(loan)),
                    poutcome = as.factor(capitalize(poutcome)),
                    y = as.factor(capitalize(y)))

# Reorder month levels
df$month <- factor(df$month, levels = c("January","February","March","April","May","June","July","August","September","October","November","December"))


# Code no previous contact information in pdays as "no contact" in poutcome
df$poutcome <- as.factor(ifelse(df$pdays < 0, "No Contact", as.character(df$poutcome)))

# Reorder poutcome levels
df$poutcome <- factor(df$poutcome, levels = c("No Contact","Other","Failure","Success"))

Dealing with Missing Values

# Imputation for missing y values
init <- mice(df, maxit=0) 
meth <- init$method
predM <- init$predictorMatrix
df <- mice(df, method=meth, predictorMatrix=predM, m=5)
df <- complete(df)

# Check for missing values
sapply(df, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))

There were five missing values in the column representing term deposit subscription(y). The confinement of missing values to this single variable suggests that this data may not be missing at random. Five values is rather inconsequential in the scope of the dataframe (3,999 total observations) but in the interest of retaining as much data as possible and mitigating bias that may be introduced with listwise deletion or mode imputation we will use multivariate imputation to generate likely replacements.

There is a moderate correlation between pdays and previous as these appear to represent similar information. The value -1 in pdays signifies that a client has not been contacted regarding a term deposit which is the same information given by a zero in previous. These values make up the majority of observations in our dataframe so may be a source of multicollinearity. In light of this we will remove pdays from the full model.

Suitability of Predictor Variables

Duration and Term Deposit Subscribership

There is a moderately strong relationship between call duration and whether a client subscribes to a term deposit. This is likely due to the additional time required for the caller to provide more information if the client shows interest. As call duration is recorded as a result of the interaction and is unknown beforehand it cannot be used as a predictor variable. All of the other variables are known prior through banking records and information from previous advertising campaigns and appear to be suitable for model building.

# Plot duration by y

  • The first of the month may have the highest proportion of subscribers but it also has the lowest number of client contacts.
  • If we had further data such as the year of last contact (which in some cases can be imputed roughly using pdays but would be unreliable) then we would be able to map these dates to days of the week and determine if there was an impact on subscription based on the weekday that contact was made. Without this further information it is unlikely that any information gleaned from this variable would be of use in this analysis.

Initial Model - All Variables

Some extreme outliers in balance may have a disproportionately large effect on the output. In order to attempt to address this we could tranform it into a categorical variable with groups defined along quartile ranges. This should mitigate the impact of extreme outliers but may also result in overfitting. We will also experiment with transforming age into a categorical variable in order to increase the uceful of any insights generated. Six age groups shall be used in order to reduce the possibility of overfitting. We will investigate differences between these full models to determine which to use as a starting point for our model selection process.

# Define account balance bands by quartiles
df <- df %>% mutate(balanceband = as.factor(case_when(balance <= 68 ~ '1',
                                         balance >= 69  & balance <= 445 ~ '2',
                                         balance >= 446  & balance <= 1470 ~ '3',
                                         balance >= 1471 ~ '4')))

Next Campaign Strategy

Conclusion

Significant Coefficients

  • Previous subscribers: The most important factor in determining if a client was to subscribe to a term deposit was their response to a previous campaign. Compared to those that had never been contacted, clients that had previous applied for a term deposit were approximately 11.35 (7.34, 17.75) times more likely to apply for one as the result of this campaign. Clients that had their previous outcome categorised as Other were 1.92 (1.23, 2.91) times more likely to subscribe than those that had never been previously been contacted.
  • Contact Type: When the method of contact is recorded as Unknown, clients are 0.32 (0.21, 0.49) times as likely to subscribe to a new term deposit than those that were contacted by mobile phone.
  • Account Balance: Clients with balances above the median were more likely to subscribe to a term deposit thank those with less money.
    • Band Three: Balances between $464 and $1470 (OR= 1.68, (1.21, 2.34))
    • Band Four: Balances above $1470 (OR= 1.79,(1.29, 2.50))
  • Personal Loan: Clients with personal loans were significantly less likely to agree to a new term deposit with the bank (OR=0.59(0.40, 0.84)).
  • Previous Campaign Contacts: Higher number of contacts correlates negatively with term deposit subscription (OR=0.93 (0.88,0.98)).
  • Occupation: We found no significant differences between professions when accounting for all other variables in the model.
  • Age: Clients between the ages of 25 and 44 were less likely than those under 25 to apply for a term deposit as a result of the campaign.
    • Age: 25-34 (OR= 0.47, (0.23, 0.99))
    • Age: 35-44 (OR= 0.44, (0.21, 0.94)) There was also weak evidence to suggest that there was a difference between those under 25 and those between the ages of 55 and 64 (OR=0.46(0.21,1.04))
  • Marital Status: Clients that were married were only 0.54 (0.39, 0.75) times as likely to apply for a term deposit than those who were divorced.
  • Month: Relative to the month of January the likelihood of a client subscribing is:
    • 2.41 (1.15, 5.19) times baseline in February
    • 6.28 (2.59, 15.46) times baseline in March
    • 2.03 (1.05, 4.11) times baseline in April
    • 3.24 (1.54, 7.02) times baseline in June
    • 2.64 (1.02, 6.76) times baseline in September
    • 6.20 (2.89, 13.74) times baseline in October

Actions for Future Campaigns

  1. Previous Customers: Focus on clients who have previously had a term deposit with the bank, this was the most important factor in determining if they would apply for a new one.
  2. Age: Prioritise contact with clients under 25 over those between the ages of 25 and 44.
  3. Campaign Contacts: Limit the number of contacts per client. Follow up calls appear to hurt the chances of a client subscribing and is not an efficient use of resources.
  4. Marital Status: Married people are less likely to apply for term deposits than their divorced counterparts so should be deprioritised.
  5. Personal Loan: It is often a better financial decision to service an existing personal loan than invest excess money in a term deposit therefore it would make sense to prioritise contacting clients that have no outstanding personal loans as they are less likely to subscribe.
  6. Account Balance: Focus on accounts with more money in them. These account holders are more likely to subscribe to a term deposit. This may be because more affluent clients can afford to tie up their money in term deposits instead of needing it constantly available.
  7. Months of Marketing Activity: Instead of making a large number of calls in May which had the lowest rate of successes, focus instead on March, June, September and October.
